When using [`ResponseEntity`][1], Spring uses a registered [`HttpMessageConverter`][2].

If you had specified a content type of `application/octet-stream`, with a body type of `byte[]`, Spring would use the [`ByteArrayHttpMessageConverter`][3] and would have sent the bytes as-is.

If you specify a content type of `text/*`, e.g. the `text/csv` you&#39;re specifying, with a body type of `String`, Spring would use the [`StringHttpMessageConverter`][4], which would encode the text as appropriate, and send it. It would be best to explicitly specify the `charset`, e.g. using content type `text/csv; charset=UTF-8`, so the client knows the character set used by the server.

Since you specified a content type of `text/csv`, but with a body type of `byte[]`, Spring is using some other [`HttpMessageConverter`][5], probably a [`ObjectToStringHttpMessageConverter`][6], with a [`ConversionService`][7] that encodes `byte[]` to `String` as Base-64.

Side note: For better performance, don&#39;t auto-flush each line of output. Turn auto-flush off and just do a final `flush()` when done.

